00:09:33.531 --> 00:09:35.741
Who the (bleep) is Bob Welch?

235
00:09:36.826 --> 00:09:38.202
(horn blows)

236
00:09:39.829 --> 00:09:41.789
(indistinct chatter)

237
00:09:44.834 --> 00:09:47.168
Okay. for the first game.
I choose Alan Parsons

238
00:09:47.169 --> 00:09:49.546
as my teammate.
but not The Project.

239
00:09:49.547 --> 00:09:51.047
I want nothing to do with them.

240
00:09:51.048 --> 00:09:52.799
We'll play Joe and Loggins.

241
00:09:52.800 --> 00:09:55.051
- Thanks for picking me. Peter.
- No problem.

242
00:09:55.052 --> 00:09:57.387
"Crosby. Stills. Nash"
to see who goes first?

243
00:09:57.388 --> 00:09:59.597
BOTH:
Crosby. Stills. Nash. shoot.

244
00:09:59.598 --> 00:10:02.767
- Nash. I win.
- No. Crosby eats Nash.

245
00:10:02.768 --> 00:10:05.770
- Stills snorts Crosby.
- What does Nash do?

246
00:10:05.771 --> 00:10:07.731
Nash smokes Stills.

247
00:10:07.732 --> 00:10:10.025
So. Kenny. "Footloose."

248
00:10:10.026 --> 00:10:12.652
Not really a song for everyone.

249
00:10:12.653 --> 00:10:16.114
Well. maybe you'd prefer my song
in<i> Caddyshack.</i> "I'm Alright."

250
00:10:16.115 --> 00:10:19.617
Wh-What. do you think I'm stupid
because I'm in a chair?

251
00:10:19.618 --> 00:10:21.411
I'll pull the tape. guy.

252
00:10:21.412 --> 00:10:24.248
The gopher sang that song.

253
00:10:28.878 --> 00:10:31.129
This is so exciting.
What do you want to do tonight?

254
00:10:31.130 --> 00:10:33.715
What if we just go see a movie?

255
00:10:33.716 --> 00:10:36.009
We can see a movie at home.
We need to go out.

256
00:10:36.010 --> 00:10:37.594
Shake things up.

257
00:10:37.595 --> 00:10:39.846
We're here to experience
new things. be other people.

258
00:10:39.847 --> 00:10:42.265
Mm-hmm.

259
00:10:42.266 --> 00:10:44.018
How much wine
have you had tonight?

260
00:10:45.561 --> 00:10:47.562
Maybe we could hang out
with that nice couple

261
00:10:47.563 --> 00:10:49.939
- we met the other day.
- The Federmans?

262
00:10:49.940 --> 00:10:52.108
Why do you always want
to hang out with other people

263
00:10:52.109 --> 00:10:53.693
when we're on vacation?

264
00:10:53.694 --> 00:10:55.737
It's just nice
to meet new people.

265
00:10:55.738 --> 00:10:59.324
Right. because I'm so interested
in the medical supply business.

266
00:10:59.325 --> 00:11:01.409
- Why do you always do that?
- Do what?

267
00:11:01.410 --> 00:11:03.370
Diminish people.

268
00:11:03.371 --> 00:11:04.788
Oh. that's why.

269
00:11:04.789 --> 00:11:07.999
Well. I feel like this has
become a referendum on me.

270
00:11:08.000 --> 00:11:10.711
and I don't appreciate it.

271
00:11:12.129 --> 00:11:14.047
Did you pack
my dandruff shampoo?

272
00:11:14.048 --> 00:11:15.548
- No.
- (sighs)

273
00:11:15.549 --> 00:11:18.218
Then I guess
this black shirt is out.

274
00:11:18.219 --> 00:11:20.595
You just want to hang out
with Doug Federman.

275
00:11:20.596 --> 00:11:23.264
What? That's...
that's the wine talking.

276
00:11:23.265 --> 00:11:25.308
What does Doug Federman have
that I don't?

277
00:11:25.309 --> 00:11:27.018
- A job.
- (grunts)

278
00:11:27.019 --> 00:11:30.397
I'm going to watch the magic
show in the Cognac Club.

279
00:11:30.398 --> 00:11:32.148
Why. because there's
a two-drink minimum?

280
00:11:32.149 --> 00:11:34.818
Oh. you shut up!

281
00:11:34.819 --> 00:11:36.277
- (applause)
- Thank you.

282
00:11:36.278 --> 00:11:38.696
For my next trick.
I'll need a volunteer.

283
00:11:38.697 --> 00:11:41.157
- How about you. sir?
- No. I don't want to!

284
00:11:41.158 --> 00:11:43.411
I don't want to do it.

285
00:11:46.372 --> 00:11:49.249
BOTH:
Bell. Biv. DeVoe. shoot.

286
00:11:49.250 --> 00:11:51.209
- (laughs) Gotcha.
- What do you mean?

287
00:11:51.210 --> 00:11:53.503
I win. Bell bivs DeVoe.

288
00:11:53.504 --> 00:11:56.214
Dude. you can't "biv" someone.
Biv's a guy.

289
00:11:56.215 --> 00:11:59.385
Everybody on this cruise
is boring.

290
00:12:01.595 --> 00:12:03.221
CHAD:
I can show you where there's

291
00:12:03.222 --> 00:12:06.433
a whole pile of those.

292
00:12:06.434 --> 00:12:07.767
Cigarette butts?

293
00:12:07.768 --> 00:12:10.353
Yeah. The wind blows them all
to this one spot.

294
00:12:10.354 --> 00:12:12.230
It's right by where
the seagulls crap.

295
00:12:12.231 --> 00:12:13.648
It's my job to clean it up.

296
00:12:13.649 --> 00:12:15.400
That's how I know about it.

297
00:12:15.401 --> 00:12:17.861
You must know a lot about crap.

298
00:12:17.862 --> 00:12:19.487
You're not from here. are you?

299
00:12:19.488 --> 00:12:21.990
From the cruise?
No. I'm from a town.

300
00:12:21.991 --> 00:12:23.950
You want to mess around
on some damp towels

301
00:12:23.951 --> 00:12:25.368
next to where the seagulls crap?

302
00:12:25.369 --> 00:12:26.828
It wasn't seagulls.

303
00:12:26.829 --> 00:12:28.538
I got locked out
of my room earlier.

304
00:12:28.539 --> 00:12:29.914
Oh.

305
00:12:29.915 --> 00:12:32.167
- Why is your poop white?
- I don't know.

306
00:12:32.168 --> 00:12:35.837
I've been dealing with
fecal albinism my whole life.

307
00:12:35.838 --> 00:12:38.840
♪ <i> All I want to do</i>
<i>in the middle of the evening</i> ♪

308
00:12:38.841 --> 00:12:41.176
♪ <i> Is hold you tight</i> ♪

309
00:12:41.177 --> 00:12:44.888
♪ <i> Rosanna. Rosanna</i> ♪

310
00:12:44.889 --> 00:12:47.265
♪ <i> I didn't know you were</i>
<i>looking for more than</i> ♪

311
00:12:47.266 --> 00:12:49.017
♪ <i> I could ever be...</i> ♪

312
00:12:49.018 --> 00:12:50.560
Hey. what are you guys up to?

313
00:12:50.561 --> 00:12:53.396
We're making a food spread
in room 103.

314
00:12:53.397 --> 00:12:54.564
Come on by.

315
00:12:54.565 --> 00:12:57.108
Grab some cocktail sauce
on your way.

316
00:12:57.109 --> 00:13:00.069
Oh. wait. Never mind.

317
00:13:00.070 --> 00:13:02.030
Aah! Damn it.

318
00:13:02.031 --> 00:13:05.576
We're watching<i> Michael Clayton</i>
on DVD later. Be there.

319
00:13:06.744 --> 00:13:08.995
(indistinct whispering)

320
00:13:08.996 --> 00:13:12.290
By the way. I. uh.
heard about Bob Welch.

321
00:13:12.291 --> 00:13:14.083
I'm sorry.

322
00:13:14.084 --> 00:13:16.503
- Don't know what else to say.
- (exhales)

323
00:13:16.504 --> 00:13:19.339
- Sending good vibes.
- Yeah...

324
00:13:19.340 --> 00:13:20.840
Can you give me a moment?

325
00:13:20.841 --> 00:13:23.968
♪ <i> Sentimental gentle wind</i> ♪

326
00:13:23.969 --> 00:13:27.305
♪ <i> Blowing through</i>
<i>my life again</i> ♪

327
00:13:27.306 --> 00:13:29.057
♪ <i> Sentimental Lady...</i> ♪

328
00:13:29.058 --> 00:13:31.643
- Bob Welch?
- Bob Welch.

329
00:13:31.644 --> 00:13:34.187
- Hey. aren't you the captain?
- Yes.

330
00:13:34.188 --> 00:13:36.815
Well. if you're here.
who's driving the boat?

331
00:13:37.942 --> 00:13:40.193
Oh. my God!

332
00:13:40.194 --> 00:13:42.363
(alarms beeping)

333
00:13:44.281 --> 00:13:47.242
Wow. I've never seen someone
eat so many powdered Donettes

334
00:13:47.243 --> 00:13:48.451
in half an hour before.

335
00:13:48.452 --> 00:13:49.661
Yeah. I was really hungry.

336
00:13:49.662 --> 00:13:51.788
and I didn't like
what they had at dinner.

337
00:13:51.789 --> 00:13:54.958
I think we may have solved
your fecal albinism.

338
00:13:54.959 --> 00:13:56.668
I love you. Meg.

339
00:13:56.669 --> 00:13:58.670
Oh. my God.

340
00:13:58.671 --> 00:14:01.005
no one's ever told me that
before.

341
00:14:01.006 --> 00:14:03.175
This is the best night
of my li...

342
00:14:06.845 --> 00:14:08.012
(screaming)

343
00:14:08.013 --> 00:14:09.348
(grunts)

344
00:14:13.477 --> 00:14:16.146
(screaming)

345
00:14:18.000 --> 00:14:24.074
Do you want subtitles for any video?
-=[ ai.OpenSubtitles.com ]=-

346
00:14:28.701 --> 00:14:31.077
(chuckles)
Listen to all those idiots fall.

347
00:14:31.078 --> 00:14:33.663
- Honey. don't revel in it.
- Hey. I need this.

348
00:14:33.664 --> 00:14:35.873
I just found out Bob Welch died.

349
00:14:35.874 --> 00:14:38.418
♪ <i> Sentimental gentle wind</i> ♪

350
00:14:38.419 --> 00:14:40.003
♪ <i> Blowing...</i> ♪

351
00:14:40.004 --> 00:14:42.755
- Aah! What are we gonna do?
- I don't know.

352
00:14:42.756 --> 00:14:46.050
And. look. Oates is hanging on
to Hall for dear life.

353
00:14:46.051 --> 00:14:47.677
(grunting)

354
00:14:47.678 --> 00:14:50.388
What else is new? He's been
doing that for 40 years.

355
00:14:50.389 --> 00:14:53.558
Ha. ha. Yeah.
make fun of more people

356
00:14:53.559 --> 00:14:55.643
more successful than you.

357
00:14:55.644 --> 00:14:57.395
He's a millionaire.

358
00:14:57.396 --> 00:14:59.398
You're nothing.

359
00:15:07.239 --> 00:15:09.241
(crying. groaning)

360
00:15:15.372 --> 00:15:17.582
Oh. thank God we're all okay.

361
00:15:17.583 --> 00:15:19.834
Looks like Oates
wasn't so lucky.

362
00:15:19.835 --> 00:15:22.212
(muffled crying. groaning)

363
00:15:28.052 --> 00:15:30.345
Guys. it's me. Kenny Loggins.

364
00:15:30.346 --> 00:15:31.888
First of all. I'm all right.

365
00:15:31.889 --> 00:15:33.097
Don't nobody worry about me.

366
00:15:33.098 --> 00:15:34.599
JOE:
Gopher!

367
00:15:34.600 --> 00:15:37.393
This boat has flipped over.
We need to get up to the hull.

368
00:15:37.394 --> 00:15:38.853
There's a spot
in the propeller room

369
00:15:38.854 --> 00:15:40.897
where the hull's
only an inch thick.

370
00:15:40.898 --> 00:15:42.815
Maybe we can try
to cut our way out...

371
00:15:42.816 --> 00:15:44.734
(screaming)

372
00:15:44.735 --> 00:15:45.861
(shouts)

373
00:15:47.321 --> 00:15:50.240
MEG:
Hey. you sons of bitches!

374
00:15:51.450 --> 00:15:52.825
This is Chad!

375
00:15:52.826 --> 00:15:55.244
He's my boyfriend.
We love each other.

376
00:15:55.245 --> 00:15:57.915
We said it and everything.

377
00:15:58.957 --> 00:16:02.168
(stifled chuckling)

378
00:16:02.169 --> 00:16:03.754
A little help?

379
00:16:07.383 --> 00:16:08.592
(grunts)

380
00:16:12.429 --> 00:16:13.555
(grunts)

381
00:16:16.850 --> 00:16:17.976
(grunts)

382
00:16:20.854 --> 00:16:22.064
(grunts)

383
00:16:28.696 --> 00:16:29.863
(grunts)

384
00:16:34.493 --> 00:16:35.993
(shouting)

385
00:16:35.994 --> 00:16:37.204
(panting)

386
00:16:41.375 --> 00:16:42.543
Hi-yah!

387
00:16:48.882 --> 00:16:50.008
(grunts)

388
00:16:51.844 --> 00:16:53.011
(grunts)

389
00:16:55.806 --> 00:16:57.807
(grunts)

390
00:16:57.808 --> 00:16:59.643
Preesh.

391
00:17:07.192 --> 00:17:08.652
(screaming)

392
00:17:14.491 --> 00:17:16.660
Guys. we got to get out of here.

393
00:17:23.000 --> 00:17:25.419
♪ ♪

394
00:17:33.177 --> 00:17:35.720
- You're alive.
- And well.

395
00:17:35.721 --> 00:17:38.181
We got to get out of here. The
water levels are rising fast.

396
00:17:38.182 --> 00:17:40.016
I'll just grab
an apple real quick.

397
00:17:40.017 --> 00:17:42.852
Granny Smith? What.
do you got a oven in your mouth?

398
00:17:42.853 --> 00:17:46.314
- Huh?
- Pie apple. It's a pie apple.

399
00:17:46.315 --> 00:17:48.232
I like a good Red Delicious.

400
00:17:48.233 --> 00:17:49.984
Oh. does your mouth
have a lid on it?

401
00:17:49.985 --> 00:17:51.569
What are you talking about?

402
00:17:51.570 --> 00:17:54.322
That's a garbage apple.
May as well eat a Honeycrisp.

403
00:17:54.323 --> 00:17:56.991
- What's wrong with that one?
- Science apple.

404
00:17:56.992 --> 00:17:59.911
Made in a lab
with test tubes and beakers.

405
00:17:59.912 --> 00:18:02.246
Well. what apples do<i> you</i> like?

406
00:18:02.247 --> 00:18:04.499
Fuji for eating.
crab for huckin'.

407
00:18:04.500 --> 00:18:06.417
That's a prankster's apple.

408
00:18:06.418 --> 00:18:09.337
Gosh. Cleveland. I had no idea
you knew so much about apples.

409
00:18:09.338 --> 00:18:12.465
- Hmm. Did you ever ask?
- No. I guess I didn't.

410
00:18:12.466 --> 00:18:13.966
Hmm.

411
00:18:13.967 --> 00:18:16.970
♪ ♪

412
00:18:22.309 --> 00:18:25.812
(grunting)
I can't open it!

413
00:18:25.813 --> 00:18:28.231
There's too much water
pushing from the other side!

414
00:18:28.232 --> 00:18:29.690
So we're stuck?

415
00:18:29.691 --> 00:18:32.276
Yeah. unless we can
somehow tip the boat.

416
00:18:32.277 --> 00:18:34.237
♪ <i> Maybe we can.</i> ♪

417
00:18:34.238 --> 00:18:36.155
What are you talking about.
Michael McDonald?

418
00:18:36.156 --> 00:18:37.865
♪ <i> The timbre in my voice</i> ♪

419
00:18:37.866 --> 00:18:40.243
♪ <i> Allows me to communicate</i>
<i>with whales.</i> ♪

420
00:18:40.244 --> 00:18:42.328
♪ <i> Maybe they can help.</i> ♪

421
00:18:42.329 --> 00:18:44.748
(high-pitched singing)

422
00:19:07.396 --> 00:19:09.022
♪ ♪

423
00:19:19.992 --> 00:19:21.410
(grunts)

424
00:19:26.331 --> 00:19:28.124
Oh. we-- oh. we found him.

425
00:19:28.125 --> 00:19:30.793
(bleep)! You guys left me
down there to drown.

426
00:19:30.794 --> 00:19:33.212
Technically. we left you
up there to drown.

427
00:19:33.213 --> 00:19:34.505
The boat flipped.

428
00:19:34.506 --> 00:19:35.798
You know what you did.

429
00:19:35.799 --> 00:19:37.925
I think the only way
to teach you a lesson

430
00:19:37.926 --> 00:19:40.219
is to dog-shake
and get you all wet.

431
00:19:40.220 --> 00:19:41.679
- No. Brian. don't!
- I'm doing it.

432
00:19:41.680 --> 00:19:44.432
(overlapping protests)

433
00:19:44.433 --> 00:19:45.725
All right. we're even.

434
00:19:45.726 --> 00:19:47.477
(creaking)

435
00:19:48.729 --> 00:19:50.396
Well. we found the thinnest part
of the hull.

436
00:19:50.397 --> 00:19:52.148
but it's still an inch thick.

437
00:19:52.149 --> 00:19:55.860
Yeah. of steel. How are we
supposed to get through that?

438
00:19:55.861 --> 00:19:57.571
(dramatic music plays)

439
00:20:09.541 --> 00:20:11.584
(all inhale deeply)

440
00:20:11.585 --> 00:20:14.504
Man. that was crazy.

441
00:20:16.673 --> 00:20:17.924
I'm Casey Kasem.

442
00:20:17.925 --> 00:20:20.217
Coming in at number seven
on the countdown.

443
00:20:20.218 --> 00:20:22.929
that was Peter Griffin
with "Yacht Rocky."

444
00:20:22.930 --> 00:20:23.930
down three spots.

445
00:20:23.931 --> 00:20:25.806
Now for our number six.

446
00:20:25.807 --> 00:20:27.558
<i>CHORUS:</i>
♪ <i> Number six.</i> ♪

447
00:20:27.559 --> 00:20:30.227
We'll start with a letter
from Melanie in Kansas.

448
00:20:30.228 --> 00:20:32.605
She writes. "Dear Casey.

449
00:20:32.606 --> 00:20:35.733
"is Christopher Cross
as nice as he seems?

450
00:20:35.734 --> 00:20:37.443
"Also. aren't you dead?

451
00:20:37.444 --> 00:20:39.695
"And why did your large wife

452
00:20:39.696 --> 00:20:41.656
"hide your body
from your children?"

453
00:20:41.657 --> 00:20:45.409
Well. the answer to your first
question is a resounding yes.

454
00:20:45.410 --> 00:20:47.912
Christopher Cross
is a perfect gentleman.

455
00:20:47.913 --> 00:20:49.413
And as for the second question.

456
00:20:49.414 --> 00:20:50.665
you're correct. Melanie.

457
00:20:50.666 --> 00:20:52.291
I'm extremely dead.

458
00:20:52.292 --> 00:20:54.919
and I do wish my children
could have closure.

459
00:20:54.920 --> 00:20:57.380
Honey.
if you're listening. please.

460
00:20:57.381 --> 00:21:00.174
just put my body in the ground.

461
00:21:00.175 --> 00:21:02.386
And now back to the countdown.

462
